# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth clarifying directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary design goals.

---

## How Rust Actually Manages Memory

Rust uses a **compile-time ownership system** to manage memory with zero runtime overhead.

### The Three Core Rules

```rust
// RULE 1: Every value has a single owner
let s = String::from("hello");  // s owns this string

// RULE 2: When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped
{
    let s = String::from("hello");
}  // s is dropped HERE - memory freed automatically, no GC needed

// RULE 3: There can only be one owner at a time
let s1 = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s1;  // ownership MOVES to s2
// println!("{}", s1);  // COMPILE ERROR - s1 no longer owns the value
```

### Borrowing (Using Without Taking Ownership)

```rust
fn calculate_length(s: &String) -> usize {  // & = borrow, don't own
    s.len()
}  // s is NOT dropped here - we don't own it

fn main() {
    let s1 = String::from("hello");
    let len = calculate_length(&s1);  // lend s1, keep ownership
    println!("{} has length {}", s1, len);  // s1 still valid
}
```

